TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technology Adoption and Productivity Growth: Evidence from Industrialization in France
AU  - Juhász, Réka
AU  - Squicciarini, Mara P.
AU  - Voigtländer, Nico
Y1  - 2024/02/27
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/730205
DO  - 10.1086/730205
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3215
EP  - 3259
VL  - 132
IS  - 10
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - New technologies tend to be adopted slowly and?even after being adopted?take time to be reflected in higher aggregate productivity. One prominent explanation is that major technological breakthroughs create the need to reorganize production. We study a unique setting that allows us to examine this mechanism: the adoption of mechanized cotton spinning during the first Industrial Revolution in France. Using a novel hand-collected, plant-level dataset from French archival sources, we show that a process of ?trial and error? in reorganizing production led to initially low and widely dispersed productivity across firms operating the new technology. In the subsequent decades, we observe high productivity growth as knowledge diffused through the economy and new entrants adopted improved methods of organizing production.
AB  - New technologies tend to be adopted slowly and?even after being adopted?take time to be reflected in higher aggregate productivity. One prominent explanation is that major technological breakthroughs create the need to reorganize production. We study a unique setting that allows us to examine this mechanism: the adoption of mechanized cotton spinning during the first Industrial Revolution in France. Using a novel hand-collected, plant-level dataset from French archival sources, we show that a process of ?trial and error? in reorganizing production led to initially low and widely dispersed productivity across firms operating the new technology. In the subsequent decades, we observe high productivity growth as knowledge diffused through the economy and new entrants adopted improved methods of organizing production.
