TY  - JOUR
T1  - Funding of Clinical Trials and Reported Drug Efficacy
AU  - Oostrom, Tamar
Y1  - 2024/03/12
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/730383
DO  - 10.1086/730383
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3298
EP  - 3333
VL  - 132
IS  - 10
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper estimates the effect of financial sponsorship of clinical trials on reported drug efficacy, leveraging the insight that the exact same pairs of drugs are often compared in different trials conducted by parties with different financial interests. I assemble new psychiatric trial data to estimate that a drug appears substantially more effective when the trial is sponsored by that drug?s manufacturer, compared with the same drug tested against the same combination of drugs but without sponsorship. This difference is not explained by observable characteristics, but publication bias is important. Preregistration may be effective in overcoming this bias.
AB  - This paper estimates the effect of financial sponsorship of clinical trials on reported drug efficacy, leveraging the insight that the exact same pairs of drugs are often compared in different trials conducted by parties with different financial interests. I assemble new psychiatric trial data to estimate that a drug appears substantially more effective when the trial is sponsored by that drug?s manufacturer, compared with the same drug tested against the same combination of drugs but without sponsorship. This difference is not explained by observable characteristics, but publication bias is important. Preregistration may be effective in overcoming this bias.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/730383
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/730383
Y2  - 2024/10/27
